        <TopCategoryHighlights isTemplate="1">
            <stf_Heading><![CDATA[Useful Tips]]></stf_Heading>
            <stf_InformationTitle><![CDATA[]]></stf_InformationTitle>
            <txt_Information><![CDATA[Prepare for your Australian trip with our practical tips. Learn about our currency, how to call home, keep safe, shop responsibly and travel with a disability. Then you’re ready to go.]]></txt_Information>
            <con_CenterContent>
                <CenterContent isTemplate="1">
                    <hdl_Title><![CDATA[Money]]></hdl_Title>
                    <img_MainImage><![CDATA[]]></img_MainImage>
                    <stf_Caption><![CDATA[]]></stf_Caption>
                    <anc_link><![CDATA[]]></anc_link>
                    <txt_Information>
                        <![CDATA[Australia’s currency is Australian Dollars (AUD) and currency exchange is available at banks, hotels and international airports. The most commonly accepted credit cards are American Express, Bankcard, Diners Club, MasterCard, Visa, JCB and their affiliates. Try this handy currency converter.]]>
                    </txt_Information>
                </CenterContent><CenterContent isTemplate="1">
                    <hdl_Title><![CDATA[Goods and Services Tax]]></hdl_Title>
                    <img_MainImage><![CDATA[]]></img_MainImage>
                    <stf_Caption><![CDATA[]]></stf_Caption>
                    <anc_link><![CDATA[]]></anc_link>
                    <txt_Information>
                        <![CDATA[Australia has a Goods and Services Tax (GST) of 10 per cent. You may be able to claim a refund of the GST paid on goods bought here if you have spent AUD$300 or more in one store, no more than 30 days before departing Australia. Tourist Refund Scheme facilities are located in the departure area of international terminals. For more detailed information see Australian government information on the <A href="http://www.customs.gov.au/site/page4643.asp" target=_blank>Tourist Refund Scheme</A>.]]>
                    </txt_Information>
                </CenterContent><CenterContent isTemplate="1">
                    <hdl_Title><![CDATA[Shopping]]></hdl_Title>
                    <img_MainImage><![CDATA[]]></img_MainImage>
                    <stf_Caption><![CDATA[]]></stf_Caption>
                    <anc_link><![CDATA[]]></anc_link>
                    <txt_Information>
                        <![CDATA[
        You’ll find large department stores, arcades, malls, gift and <a href="/explore/things-to-do/shopping/australian-souvenirs.xml" target="_self">souvenir shops</a> across Australia. Trading hours vary across the country but shops in tourist and city areas are generally open until 6pm, with the exception of late night shopping on either Thursdays or Fridays in different states. In Australia you are covered by <a href="http://www.ret.gov.au/tourism/Documents/Tourism/Tourism%20Policy/China%20Approved%20Desitnation%20Scheme/0997%20Consumer%20rights%20v3.pdf" target="_blank">Australia's consumer protection laws</a> which require businesses to treat you fairly.
    ]]>
                    </txt_Information>
                </CenterContent><CenterContent isTemplate="1">
                    <hdl_Title><![CDATA[Tipping and bargaining]]></hdl_Title>
                    <img_MainImage><![CDATA[]]></img_MainImage>
                    <stf_Caption><![CDATA[]]></stf_Caption>
                    <anc_link><![CDATA[]]></anc_link>
                    <txt_Information>
                        <![CDATA[Hotels and restaurants do not add service charges to your bill. In up market restaurants, it is usual to tip waiters up to ten per cent of the bill for good service. However, tipping is always your choice. It is not custom to bargain in Australia. ]]>
                    </txt_Information>
                </CenterContent><CenterContent isTemplate="1">
                    <hdl_Title><![CDATA[Emergency assistance]]></hdl_Title>
                    <img_MainImage><![CDATA[]]></img_MainImage>
                    <stf_Caption><![CDATA[]]></stf_Caption>
                    <anc_link><![CDATA[]]></anc_link>
                    <txt_Information>
                        <![CDATA[The emergency number for police, ambulance and or fire brigade is 000.]]>
                    </txt_Information>
                </CenterContent><CenterContent isTemplate="1">
                    <hdl_Title><![CDATA[Surf and water safety]]></hdl_Title>
                    <img_MainImage><![CDATA[]]></img_MainImage>
                    <stf_Caption><![CDATA[]]></stf_Caption>
                    <anc_link><![CDATA[]]></anc_link>
                    <txt_Information>
                        <![CDATA[
        Australia’s popular beaches are usually patrolled by volunteer lifesavers from October to April and red and yellow flags mark the safest area for swimming. For information about marine stingers and crocodile safety read the <a href="http://www.qld.gov.au/emergency/safety/dangerous-marine.html" target="_blank">Queensland Government</a> website. 
    ]]>
                    </txt_Information>
                </CenterContent><CenterContent isTemplate="1">
                    <hdl_Title><![CDATA[Language]]></hdl_Title>
                    <img_MainImage><![CDATA[]]></img_MainImage>
                    <stf_Caption><![CDATA[]]></stf_Caption>
                    <anc_link><![CDATA[]]></anc_link>
                    <txt_Information>
                        <![CDATA[Australia’s official language is English. However, being a multicultural nation with a significant migrant population, we also enjoy a tremendous diversity of languages and cultures. ]]>
                    </txt_Information>
                </CenterContent><CenterContent isTemplate="1">
                    <hdl_Title><![CDATA[Electrical power points]]></hdl_Title>
                    <img_MainImage><![CDATA[]]></img_MainImage>
                    <stf_Caption><![CDATA[]]></stf_Caption>
                    <anc_link><![CDATA[]]></anc_link>
                    <txt_Information>
                        <![CDATA[Our electrical current is 220 – 240 volts, AC 50Hz. The Australian three-pin power outlet is different from some other countries, so you may need an adaptor.]]>
                    </txt_Information>
                </CenterContent><CenterContent isTemplate="1">
                    <hdl_Title><![CDATA[Communication]]></hdl_Title>
                    <img_MainImage><![CDATA[]]></img_MainImage>
                    <stf_Caption><![CDATA[]]></stf_Caption>
                    <anc_link><![CDATA[]]></anc_link>
                    <txt_Information>
                        <![CDATA[Australia’s country code is 61. Local calls from public pay phones are untimed and charged at AUD$.050. Mobile, long distance and overseas calls are usually timed.Mobile phone network coverage is available across Australia, however coverage may be limited in some remote areas. Internet access is widely available at internet cafes, accommodation and libraries.]]>
                    </txt_Information>
                </CenterContent><CenterContent isTemplate="1">
                    <hdl_Title><![CDATA[Postal services]]></hdl_Title>
                    <img_MainImage><![CDATA[]]></img_MainImage>
                    <stf_Caption><![CDATA[]]></stf_Caption>
                    <anc_link><![CDATA[]]></anc_link>
                    <txt_Information>
                        <![CDATA[Post offices are usually open 9am – 5pm, Monday to Friday, with some city post offices open on Saturday morning. Travellers can arrange to collect mail at post offices throughout Australia.]]>
                    </txt_Information>
                </CenterContent><CenterContent isTemplate="1">
                    <hdl_Title><![CDATA[Accessible Travel]]></hdl_Title>
                    <img_MainImage><![CDATA[]]></img_MainImage>
                    <stf_Caption><![CDATA[]]></stf_Caption>
                    <anc_link><![CDATA[]]></anc_link>
                    <txt_Information>
                        <![CDATA[If you have a disability and are planning to explore Australia, there is a host of services and special deals to meet your needs. Thorough preparation is essential to a successful trip, so speak to your travel agent about your specific requirements. For more information on accessible tourism in Australia go to <A href="http://www.nican.com.au/" target=_blank>NICAN</A> or the <A href="http://www.australiaforall.com/" target=_blank>AustraliaForAll</A>&nbsp; websites.]]>
                    </txt_Information>
                </CenterContent>
            </con_CenterContent>
